To represent the logical expression ¬(p∧q) in a simple circuit diagram, we first need to understand its meaning:

¬ - means negation, which is the NOT operation.
(p∧q) - means p AND q, where the operation "∧" stands for conjunction.

So, ¬(p∧q) means NOT (p AND q), which is logically equivalent to (¬p OR ¬q) or in terms of inputs (+ for powered, - for not powered):

- If either p OR q is not powered (¬p OR ¬q), the output O will be powered (+).
- If both p AND q are powered, the output O will be not powered (-).

Following the given format for the circuit diagram, the representation is:

[[p, q], output]; 
[(-, -), (-); 
(+, -), (-); 
(-, +), (-); 
(+, +), (+)]

This representation shows all possible combinations of inputs and their corresponding outputs in the circuit diagram.

